          "label": "<p>Which of the following is NOT a structure or level marked by the sternal angle (</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following is NOT a structure or level marked by the sternal angle (Angle of Louis)?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Second costal cartilage</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The second costal cartilage is located at the sternal angle, making it the clinical starting point for counting ribs.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bifurcation of the trachea</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The tracheal bifurcation into the right and left main bronchi is one of the five structures marked by the sternal angle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Disc between T2 and T3 vertebrae</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The sternal angle corresponds to the disc between T4 and T5, not T2 and T3. This posterior landmark sits approximately five centimetres below the jugular notch.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Boundary between superior and inferior mediastinum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sternal angle does mark the boundary between the superior and inferior mediastinum — the horizontal dividing plane passes through it anteriorly.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The sternal angle corresponds to the T4/T5 disc posteriorly, not T2/T3. Remember its five landmarks: 2nd costal cartilage, tracheal bifurcation, aortic arch, T4/T5 disc, and mediastinum boundary."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The sternal angle marks five structures: the 2nd costal cartilage, tracheal bifurcation, aortic arch, the T4/T5 disc, and the superior–inferior mediastinum boundary."
                }
              ],
