          "label": "<p>Why can a myocardial infarction cause referred pain along the medial aspect of t</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Why can a myocardial infarction cause referred pain along the medial aspect of the upper arm?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The first intercostal nerve directly innervates the myocardium</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>T1 sends most of its fibres into the brachial plexus and has a small remaining portion with no cutaneous branches. It does not directly innervate the myocardium.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The intercostobrachial nerve (T2) crosses the axilla to supply the medial arm skin</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The second intercostal nerve gives off the intercostobrachial nerve, which crosses the axilla to supply the skin of the inner upper arm. Cardiac afferent fibres enter the spinal cord at similar thoracic levels, causing the brain to misinterpret the pain source.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The phrenic nerve carries cardiac afferents to the arm</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The phrenic nerve (C3–C5) supplies the diaphragm and pericardium but does not carry afferents to the arm.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Thoraco-abdominal nerves (T7–T11) extend into the upper limb</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Thoraco-abdominal nerves leave the thorax and enter the anterior abdominal wall — they do not extend into the upper limb.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The intercostobrachial nerve, a lateral cutaneous branch of the second intercostal nerve, crosses the axilla to supply the skin of the inner upper arm. Because cardiac pain afferents enter the cord at similar thoracic levels, the brain refers the pain to the arm."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The intercostobrachial nerve (lateral cutaneous branch of T2) is the anatomical basis for cardiac referred pain in the medial arm."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
