          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During inspiration, bucket-handle movement of the lower ribs (7–10) primarily in</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During inspiration, bucket-handle movement of the lower ribs (7–10) primarily increases which dimension of the thoracic cavity?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anteroposterior (front-to-back) diameter</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The anteroposterior diameter is increased primarily by pump-handle movement of the upper ribs (2–6), where the sternum moves forward and upward.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transverse (side-to-side) diameter</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Bucket-handle movement describes the lower ribs flaring laterally when they elevate. Their axis of rotation runs front-to-back through the costovertebral and costotransverse joints, so the outer curve swings outward.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vertical (superior-to-inferior) height</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The vertical height of the thorax is increased by diaphragmatic contraction and descent, not by rib movement.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anteroposterior diameter, similar to pump-handle movement</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Pump-handle and bucket-handle movements affect different dimensions. Pump-handle (upper ribs) increases the anteroposterior diameter; bucket-handle (lower ribs) increases the transverse diameter. Their distinct axes of rotation produce these different effects.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Bucket-handle movement increases the transverse (side-to-side) diameter. Think of a bucket handle lifting — the midpoint swings outward. The lower ribs do exactly this, flaring laterally when they elevate."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Remember the analogy: a bucket handle lifts at the midpoint and swings outward, just as the lower ribs flare laterally to widen the transverse diameter."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
