          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>If a mass in the superior mediastinum expands, which pair of structures would both be at risk of compression?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both the ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk lie in the middle mediastinum, below the plane of the sternal angle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Trachea and oesophagus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Both the trachea and oesophagus pass through the superior mediastinum, along with the aortic arch, superior vena cava, thoracic duct, vagus and phrenic nerves, and the thymus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Heart and descending aorta</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The heart lies in the middle mediastinum and the descending aorta in the posterior mediastinum — neither is in the superior mediastinum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Azygos vein and sympathetic trunks</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both the azygos vein and sympathetic trunks lie in the posterior mediastinum, behind the pericardium.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The trachea and oesophagus both pass through the superior mediastinum. Remember: the dividing plane runs from the sternal angle anteriorly to the T4/T5 disc posteriorly. Structures above this plane are in the superior mediastinum."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The superior mediastinum is a crowded space above the sternal angle plane, containing major airways, vessels, nerves, and the thymus."
                }
              ],
